The Federal Reserve, traditionally insulated from day-to-day politics, was pulled into the same vortex. President Trump publicly called for the resignation of Governor Lisa Cook, the first Black woman to serve on the Fed\'92s board, after a housing official aligned with him referred allegations of mortgage fraud to the Justice Department. He threatened to fire her if she did not step down, a move that would give him another seat to fill and further reshape the central bank. The Justice Department opened an investigation into the claims. Whatever the merits of the underlying allegations, the sequence\'97referral from a political ally, presidential demand for resignation, criminal probe\'97signaled that even the Fed\'92s governors were not beyond the reach of partisan pressure. Monetary policy itself was now in the shadow of political threat.\
