U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services expanded its own social media screening, instructing officers to look for ideological content that might suggest applicants were promoting ideas contrary to U.S. interests. A new policy memo called for a more \'93rigorous, holistic and comprehensive\'94 approach to evaluating citizenship applicants\'92 \'93good moral character,\'94 relying on subjective judgments about behavior and societal norms. At the same time, a federal appeals court allowed the administration to move forward, at least temporarily, with ending Temporary Protected Status for more than 60,000 immigrants from Nicaragua, Honduras, and Nepal. A separate federal judge upheld Illinois\'92s right to maintain a workplace privacy law that limited employer cooperation with immigration enforcement, and another ruled that the State Department could not deny certain visas solely on the basis of the president\'92s travel ban. But the overall direction was clear. For millions of noncitizens, presence in the country and access to legal status now depended not only on conduct but on perceived loyalty and alignment with the regime\'92s values.\
