Against this backdrop, the administration\'92s approach to truth and public memory took on greater weight. At the Environmental Protection Agency, loyalists moved to rescind the 2009 endangerment finding that had underpinned federal regulation of greenhouse gases, despite the scientific consensus on climate change. The Treasury Department rewrote long-standing standards for renewable energy tax credits, making it harder for clean energy projects to qualify and contributing to rising electricity prices. Health Secretary Robert F. Kennedy Jr. terminated twenty-two projects worth $500 million aimed at developing mRNA vaccines for respiratory viruses and accused the American Academy of Pediatrics of running a \'93pay-to-play scheme\'94 with pharmaceutical companies. More than 750 current and former federal health workers wrote to him and to Congress, warning that his rhetoric had fueled harassment and violence, including a deadly shooting at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention\'92s Atlanta headquarters. Science itself was being cast as suspect when it clashed with political storylines.\
