The president\'92s interventions in cultural institutions followed the same pattern. On social media and through official channels, he criticized the Smithsonian Institution for focusing \'93too much\'94 on how bad slavery was and on \'93how horrible our country is.\'94 He directed his attorneys to review the museums\'92 exhibits, echoing earlier campaigns against universities. The White House published an article attacking Smithsonian displays on race, slavery, trans identity, and immigration. These moves did not yet rewrite a single label on a wall, but they signaled that the federal government now claimed a say in how the nation\'92s history of injustice would be told. Museums, like agencies and courts, were being drawn into the orbit of loyalty and control. Memory was no longer just recorded; it was curated from above.\
