Not every institution bent. Federal judges blocked Texas\'92s law mandating Ten Commandments displays in public school classrooms, citing the First Amendment\'92s separation of church and state. They ordered the closure of the \'93Alligator Alcatraz\'94 immigration jail in the Florida Everglades within sixty days, citing environmental damage and human rights concerns, and barred the state from bringing in new detainees while parts of the facility were dismantled. Another judge ruled that Alina Habba, a former Trump lawyer, had been unlawfully serving as U.S. attorney for New Jersey, faulting the administration\'92s efforts to keep her in the role without Senate confirmation. A federal court dismissed the administration\'92s challenge to Illinois\'92s workplace privacy law, preserving a state\'92s ability to shield workers from certain immigration-related inquiries. And in Iowa, a Democrat, Catelin Drey, won a special state senate election, breaking the Republican supermajority and giving her party new leverage over appointments. These were real checks, not just gestures.\
