Yet even these pockets of resistance sat alongside rulings that favored the powerful. The New York appellate court that overturned a $500 million civil fraud penalty against Donald Trump did so on Eighth Amendment grounds, calling the fine excessive, even as it affirmed that he had inflated asset values. The Florida Supreme Court\'92s approval of a map that gutted Black representation, and the Texas judge\'92s order constraining a Democratic fundraising group, showed courts aligning with partisan and elite interests on core questions of representation and power. The same judiciary that closed a detention center and blocked a religious mandate also allowed Temporary Protected Status terminations to proceed and left in place business restrictions on the former president that were lighter than the original penalty. The check was partial and uneven.\
