Looking ahead from this week, several processes were already in motion. The Election Assistance Commission had opened a public comment period on a petition to require documentary proof of citizenship for federal voter registration, a change that could reshape who is able to sign up to vote. California\'92s mid-decade redistricting plan was headed to a November special election, promising a national fight over the legitimacy of partisan counter-gerrymanders. The courts would continue to hear challenges to the Alligator Alcatraz closure order, the Texas redistricting map, and the use of military forces in Los Angeles. The Justice Department\'92s investigation into Federal Reserve Governor Lisa Cook, and the president\'92s threats to remove her, would test the resilience of central bank independence. And the continuous vetting of tens of millions of visa holders, largely invisible to the public, would proceed in the background, reshaping lives one revocation at a time.\
\
By the end of Week 31, the Democracy Clock\'92s movement to 7:57 p.m. captured a subtle but important shift. The country was not yet in open dictatorship; elections still occurred, courts still sometimes ruled against the president, and civil society still protested. But the balance between law as a limit and law as a weapon had tilted further toward the latter. Executive power operated with fewer effective checks, especially in the realms of policing, immigration, and information. Security forces were increasingly aligned with the preservation of the regime rather than the defense of the public. Citizenship and basic safety were more tightly stratified by origin, ideology, and perceived loyalty. And the stories the nation told itself\'97about its past, its science, and its economy\'97were more subject to political editing.\
